What's up? The SSD in Prague knows neither Voldemort nor the pastry shop
The new SSD councillors in the capital are reportedly going to have to overcome obvious language barriers for the Prague Board and City Council components to understand their renewed SDG partners.
The period Aktuáln?.cz "examined" the members of the new Council of the SSD to check their knowledge of the slang marked language that has emerged in recent years in the Council, when the current members of the coalition ruled Prague.
The codified dictionary that used the political flower and cream of Prague during the previous period, by Mayor Pavel Bém, includes some of the most well-known characters, situations and causes of the metropolis.
Surprisingly, it has been proven that the new councilors hardly understand these well-known concepts.
At least, so they say.
"Who is Voldemort?"
"The truth is, I don't know."
"Rather I am a novice in Prague politics," said during the examination of terminology of "collegiate" the councilor of culture Lukas Kaucky.
And as far as the veteran politician was concerned, Karel Boezina reacted as well.
You may know the concept of "golf hole."
"Possibly the only expression of all the ones you asked me to use from time to time."
"If not, I don't normally employ slang."
From the glossary, whose definitions were published by the newspaper Aktuáln.cz last June before the SDG voting congress, the editorial staff chose six examples, in particular those that are especially related to Prague’s municipal authorities.
Socialists had to explain the concepts "Voldemort", "Prague's biggest golf hole", "going to the pastry shop", "bull's nest", "betrayal of the capital" and "blinding".
Three councillors agreed to the test and a fourth, Antonín Weinert, who will be responsible for education in Prague in the future, initially agreed, but did not pick up the phone again.
The fifth councilman, Petr Dolínek, directly refused to do so.
“I don’t get into these things and I don’t think I’m going to value how civic democrats are having fun.”
“What I do care about is how we will understand each other in the execution of our programs,” he said.
As has been seen, Councilman Luká? Kauck? allegedly did not realize that the above title is an expression about an influential businessman and a friend of former Mayor Bém, Roman Janou?ek.
The word "Voldemort" doesn't say anything to Kauck; the only term he got right on the exam is "the biggest golf hole in Prague."
“It’s about the Blanka tunnel,” says Kaucka, who immediately adds: “But I rather know it from the news.”
“I’m going to have to sign up for a language course,” he jokes.
Karel Boezina is not the only one who recognizes the Blanka tunnel in the golf hole, but also the Councillor for the Environment Luka Plach.
Afterward, both socio-democrats know who Voldemort and Lukas Plach really are – they even know where to find that character; moreover, they suspect the meaning of "going to the bakery".
"I think it means to go to a company in Prague"; soon it is revealed to Placha that it is the headquarters of the companies in Janou?ek.
Like B?ezina, it indicates that such knowledge was gained from the news, but that it does not employ such vocabulary.
According to the participants in the test, among the socio-democrats there is no glossary so familiar in colloquial terms.
"I asked my teammates, but we don't really seem to have anything like it."
“Rather, among us we use nicknames, sometimes abbreviations or puns with names,” says Prague SSD president Petr Hulinsk, whose party colleagues call Hulda.
“At school they called me B?iza, but I don’t know if my classmates call me that too,” confesses her own nickname Karel B?ezina.
The newspaper Aktuáln?.cz tested the name and it works.
To his party mates, Weinert is D?da (similar to "yay") or, less friendly, D?dek ("old"), Representative Miroslav Poche, with whom he partnered before the election deceptions during the party's sponsorship, is nicknamed "Igrá?ek" ("playmobil") by some of his peers.
Nicknames are also the only expressions that socio-democrats tolerate in speech within the party.
Hulinsk doesn’t like to be called Hulda, but the newspaper Aktuáln.cz discovered even other nicknames for this Prague president.
"The doctor of baton rights" apparently remembers that Petr Hulinski obtained his doctorate in Law at the police academy in Bratislava.
The government wants to limit the torture of “witches”, as it published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually elderly, unable to work, for example, for health reasons, are single and do not have children.
Women who “turn” witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such a fate."
“You also don’t isolate healthy young women, because they help in the work and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, works in a special residence of more than a hundred women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual “social measure”.
He issued an information booklet that should help prevent the witch hunt.
However, this has a downside.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso do not know how to read,” warns the newspaper Die Standard about the disadvantages of sensitization in writing.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, Burkina Faso’s neighbor, Ammy Hemmah, 72, died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to an unfortunate accumulation of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was lit in the oil that is used for ritual anointings.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "eject evil spirits" from the woman.
The isolation of “witches” is supported by people of all educational levels.
The Der Standard newspaper quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso: “Human soul-eaters have always been a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government is trying to quell the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president was still involved.
Gambian President Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging hunt for witches who had allegedly been linked to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself through black magic.
“To help him he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly chosen men and women from Gambian villages to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused them intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay at the estate.
Following international pressure, they eventually released around a thousand detainees.
Bakala tenant: heats up with coal stoves and signs a higher rent
The elderly and tough man walked through the doors of the customer service center of the RPG company Byty of the "coal magnate" Zde?ek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried documents with the new three-story rental contracts: his own, that of his daughter and that of his son, who is serving a sentence.
All three have just been hit with rent liberalization.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns a month, the son will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-room flat with separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," shows with the finger the man in the new contract of his son, over whose signature he has full powers.
“But I signed it,” he explains half-angry, half-resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions “incorrect and indecent”, recommends tenants not to sign the new contracts and to wait until December 7, the date on which it will publish a guide informing on how to proceed in these cases.
But, before this, the man only makes a gesture.
“Everyone says one thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major testing ground for liberalisation.
After New Year it will happen with the vast majority of the flats that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktuáln.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of the four in Ostrava and, by Tuesday at nine o’clock, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to collect numbers.
"Rent 2011" can be read on a bright button on your touch screen.
When pressed, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
Almost no time to read "157" and the number appears on the big screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly couple arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, such as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues, and the like.
The letters with the new leases will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of the tenants of most of the 44,000 flats belonging to RPG around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the cards an increase in rent of between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
“It’s been going on for a week, so it’s starting,” respond, after briefly doubting, the workers who are in it when the client introduces themselves as a journalist.
Liberalization and Bakala’s former miners’ flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, the vice-president of the Ostrava-based parliament, Lubomír Zaorálek of the SSD, already treated them loud and clear and now they appear continuously in newspapers in the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
“They didn’t even change my fucking bathroom plate,” says the man mentioned in the introduction.
According to the workers, for the moment they come mostly retired to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign on time, as the special RPG offer promises.
Half of the February rent discount will also be received by the remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15.
However, the window of mining “liberalization” certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about rent in 2011 about forty or fifty people," estimates the window employee.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rental, an independent judge must resolve the issue.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only way to proceed as possible and completely in accordance with the law," the RPG warns in its pages.
“No one’s going to be judged here,” says one of RPG Byty’s employees, and a man standing on the street in front of the customer service center is at least partly right.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means of going to court,” he says.
But, immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
“Mr. Zaoralek warns them in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait,” he says.
Rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic at the beginning of 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“Current rents still don’t cover even the amounts needed to maintain the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klime, director of the residential portfolio of RPG company Byty, adding that the neglected state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for landlords, the main reason for increasing rent.
While during the five years that elapsed between 2005 and 2010 RPG could with the rents invest in apartments four billion, in the four years that will go from 2011 to 2014 the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, that is, more than 90% of RPG properties."
“In addition, there will always be a maximum of 7.50 Czech kroner per square meter,” the statement said.
It only increased by 38% the rental of 400 flats of the RPG portfolio.
“In such cases, it’s an increase from extremely low amounts of 19.66 crowns per square meter,” says RPG.
In 2,600 flats, rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalisation will not suddenly affect rents, but will escalate between four to eight years.
In addition, it adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the increase in rent (see the graph) again in the floors, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the rent increase agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the Arch.Design company.
No one would say that it also hides in its interior a small nursery with everything appropriate to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October of last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can come to it.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose studio came numerous well-known buildings of Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-care.
The company employs around 90 people, mainly in the baby boom age and wanted to allow female architects and draftsmen to return to work soon after motherhood.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers its workers within the framework of its social program.
The builders and architects thus have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-care was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-care is financed through the European Social Fund under the Operational Programme for Human Resources and Employment, as well as the State budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (an endowment of more than CZK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, to hire qualified personnel and services.
When the funding runs out (two years), the Arch.Design company has the obligation to keep the mini-store running with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and in the submission of the funding application contributed the company Economy Rating.
The care of children is provided by qualified personnel; a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present all day for their care; the daycare centre currently accommodates children with no age limit, although most of them are under three years of age.
Since it is a "mini-housekeeper", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with the shifts they come more during the day.
The functioning of the daycare is flexible to suit the needs of parents and children of all workers have the same right to use the daycare, regardless of hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual teaching and care, the contents of the mini-care program are comparable to the regular preschool program.
In it, children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school readiness, they teach to English.
The class not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up children late from school when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a relationship of loyalty between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design is among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, in short, this program reinforced the personnel marketing.
The house of bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Look at Gaudí’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs are reminiscent of a dinosaur column and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batlló, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
Due to its skeleton-like shape, locals nicknamed it "the house of bones."
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of the scales and the omnipresent gently curved lines, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaudí.
The front of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and wildlife.
Paying more attention, a certain geometry, rhythm and carefully thought order is observed.
At night, the entire facade of the house seems even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snaking and twisting the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
Wavy wood copies window frames, railings, door trims, peepholes, and signs.
Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample district at number 43 in the lively shopping street of Passeig de Grácia, emerged from the remodeling of a house from 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batlló, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaudí’s idea of making a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batlló, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaudí alone.
The architect Josep María Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project, ornaments emerged for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
On the facade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batlló was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Milá and Gaudi’s Park Guell, in which other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic form, locals soon after its completion nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening the windows began to call it "the house of yawning".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motifs.
Gaudí designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
It may seem strange its inclination of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not respect at all the building rules of the moment and did not allow himself to be influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although obviously in it the indicated data on the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, upon its completion, the city council was so shocked with the result that it asked to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even up to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented out to a jewelry store.
The six-storey house is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting space.
The common part can be completely connected by opening the doors of the salons and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with Gaudí’s reconstruction, not only got a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white and blue tiles that cover the interior courtyard and skylights.
The play with the two colors provides maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb the sun’s rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batlló, which in 2005 was added to UNESCO’s World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and busiest apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and extended visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The entrance fee to the monument is not insignificant, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaudí constructions in the city.
