How to choose the mattress and the box spring: women and men look for different things
Nothing of a pompous frame for the bed; what really confers its quality to a good bed is the surface to lie on, that is, the mattress and the box spring.
First of all, they must be complemented perfectly so that they adapt to the specific users.
During the election numerous elements come into play, including the weight, height, state of health and sex of the owner.
Also important is the type of interior in which the mattress and box spring are located.
A typical example?
For example, in a weekend cabin that does not usually have heating, latex mattresses should not be used because they "heat up" more slowly.
In addition, they usually weigh considerably more than the usual polyurethane mattresses.
Therefore, it is necessary to turn them more frequently.
If the channels in the center are not properly aerated and, above, they are on a firm base, they keep moisture inside. Mold can even appear underneath.
When choosing a bed, habits also influence.
Anyone who has spent a lot of time abroad often uses a very high mattress with a soft layer and will have trouble feeling good on a lower, harder surface.
“Almost every hockey player who came back from the NHL complained that they didn’t sleep as well here.”
"For their crushed shoulders, heels and hips they needed mattresses with a soft layer of viscoelastic."
"These types of mattresses are also recommended for people with diabetes who have long-standing nervous system problems, so they get bad information from the joints and skin," explains Sylva Hadamcziková, who specializes in padded furniture.
Many hockey players, like other customers, have long preferred viscoelastic mattresses.
"Today there is no problem, because they have these suitable Tempur and Italian Magniflex, but also the Czech brand Tropico."
You no longer have to be an NHL player to appreciate viscoelastic.
This "miracle" works in a very simple way.
It optimizes its stiffness and shape based on the heat absorbed or adapts to your body heat.
Nothing exerts pressure; during the night, it will not spin like after a hard game.
It just sleeps better.
Viscoelastic also works as a protection against sores.
When choosing the size of the mattress, add to its height the length of your feet, that is, between 21 and 34 cm.
A man or woman with a height of around 180 cm will need a bed between 210 and 220 cm.
The minimum width for a person should be, in a double room, 90 cm, in total 180 cm.
In the case of single rooms, for example single rooms, it is recommended at least between 120 and 140 cm.
So that a possible visit is also comfortable.
"If not, a simple rule can be applied to calculate the width: when lying on your back, you should have your hands comfortably shrunk towards your elbows," advises engineer Helena Prokopová, an expert from Cechu "alounik" to dekoratér, who has been dealing with the problem of healthy sleep and ergonomics of furniture for many years, a subject she teaches in specialized schools.
In double rooms, each needs its own box spring and mattress, so during the purchase you have to pay attention to combine the height of the mattresses.
Otherwise, it will be necessary to mount the bed bases at different heights, which is not always possible in all beds.
Foam mattresses should have a minimum height of 14 cm, models with spring interior a minimum of 15 cm, of which at least three centimeter are for the layer that adapts to the shapes and softens.
“Touching it with your hand or sitting on the mattress, you certainly shouldn’t notice the docks,” Helena Prokopová warns.
Each mattress requires a certain type of box spring.
Fully padded bedrooms, in which the mattress and base are like conjoined twins, make no sense in the bedroom.
Mattresses breathe badly and you can not wash your cover, which is often done today.
And, since every night we sweat between 0.2 and 0.75 l of sweat, it is clear that after about five or seven years the mattress will begin to remind us of a large (and congested) sieve.
For this reason, specialists reject slogans that speak of a mattress life of up to 25 years or even a lifetime guarantee.
However, everything has a but.
That’s why sellers give a tip: on mattresses with a width of 120 or 140 cm, take care of the cleaning and washing of the cover, but better add a mattress protector that can be easily removed and washed.
Although mattress covers with zip closure are currently manufactured throughout their perimeter, so when opened they remain in two parts (something very important for washing and the size of the washing machine!), their manipulation in the largest models (and by only one person) when lifting the mattress can seem like a fight between a flyweight and a heavy weight.
In bed, instead of a box spring, do you have a firm board?
Never!
As much for the beds designed for overnight visits.
However, it must make (if you do not already have them) ventilation holes in the table and must be used with a mattress with springs inside and a minimum height of 15 cm with springs in bags (such as the German Taschenfederkern) and a soft layer.
Polyurethane mattresses should not be used on such bases.
Latex mattresses or sandwich mattresses (for example, a combination of latex and coconut fiber) can be used for non-articulating sheet bed frames and containing between 14 and 18 sheets, although a box spring with a greater number of sheets, 28 or more, in which the sheets of the lumbar area are reinforced and their rigidity can be regulated is always better.
Articulable sheet bed bases should not be used with a spring mattress, as it does not react to reclining.
In addition to adjusting the stiffness of the blades, shoulder protection can also be used.
This is a special fixation of the sheets that allows you to press or even tilt the sheets in such a way that they "surround" the shoulders perfectly during sleep.
For men who have very wide shoulders, this is very important.
They are even remembered by mattress manufacturers who, in the "masculine", began to use a softer area precisely around the shoulders.
They also remember women, for whom they put a softer area around the hips.
For the most demanding customers, there are box springs with cross structure or slats with so-called multi-twist damping.
The pressure is distributed between different points and the tension is lowered.
You should also keep in mind that even if you use the right mattress and box spring, if you use a bad pillow (big and "mullida"), most of the advantages will disappear.
The basic rule is simple: the pillow must hold the head and the corners can only reach up to the shoulders, so that the muscles of the same can be relaxed.
The recommended appropriate size is 50 x 60 cm, something normal for example in Scandinavia.
When lying on your side, the pillow should be at the same level (when combined with the box spring with shoulder reinforcement or the softer area of the mattress) as the height of the shoulders.
Modern mattresses have something to do, it seems, with the original mattresses filled with straw.
Manufacturers continue to use, more and more often, natural materials or, at least, mixtures.
In fact, biological mattresses are in fashion.
Petroleum-based raw materials, from which polyurethane foam is manufactured, are filled with natural oils, for example castor oil or soybean oil.
In fact, virtually all known manufacturers use soy.
“Biologically, in the case of mattresses, it means that the center is made only of materials of natural origin,” explains Petr Vazícek of Tropico Plus.
Also, natural substances are used during the manufacture of the mattress cover, one of the first aloe vera.
But you can also opt for microcapsules, which release a fresh aroma of forest or lavender.
There are also differences for men and women.
While men are "cooled" with plant extracts of breeze, for the mattress cover to absorb heat and cool the body, women prefer to "warm up" the cover.
Red pepper extract improves the circulation of the blood, so that women feel more warmth.
The favorites now?
Mattresses made of cold foam, which are more porous, with a structure of adapted cells, which makes them more permeable than those of normal polyurethane and offer more permeability.
The combination of different rigidities of cold foam and viscoelastic allow to manufacture mattresses of different areas that know perfectly where the head, shoulders and heels go.
A good quality mattress will cost you seven thousand crowns up.
Those who play a therapeutic role usually have a lower VAT, since they are considered as health means.
The first to gain this advantage in the Czech Republic was Gumotex.
It is difficult to save on mattresses and box springs.
Sometimes you can approve offers from manufacturers or sellers, who sometimes offer two mattresses for the price of one.
For example, the Magniflex brand offers Duofreeze mattresses with a memory foam attached to the case for 11,990 crowns.
The second is available for free.
The era of viscoelastic with an open cell structure and high density began with Tempur's "cosmic" material.
It initially emerged as a material for NASA, because during the takeoffs the astronauts were subjected to a huge overload.
Tempur softens with heat and hardens with cold.
Therefore, the human body, warm, exerts a perfect effect and optimally adapts its pressure.
Therefore, it is ideal to prevent sores from occurring, but also to improve comfort during sleep.
Memory foam is not only used in mattresses, but also for sanitary products, for example for pillows that are placed under the legs and relieve them, as well as their circulation.
Domestic manufacturers, for example, use Eucatherm C or Twinsaver foam and the like.
More and more parents are using people tracking devices to monitor their children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about GPS monitoring.
The system, initially designed for vehicle tracking, can also track the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in the case of the disappearance of the nine-year-old girl Anika Janatková.
At the moment the device is about the size of a matchbox, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a watch.
Many people were afraid of the case of the missing Ani?ka and began to report on the means available to better protect their children.
Even at the cost of invading your privacy.
“We’re all trying to tell ourselves that it’s not about spying, but about another means of reducing the chances of a tragedy occurring,” said Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the Czech market’s leading providers of tracking devices.
“I recognize that in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they get into someone’s bag without their knowledge, but we have not yet come across such cases.”
“Most customers actually buy it for security reasons,” Pilin adds.
In his opinion, children should always know what the “box” is for and how it is used in an emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Boková warns that, if the child does not want to wear it, he will simply throw it away.
“Even the youngest children show great creativity when it comes to intentionally losing certain things if they want to avoid being controlled.”
“Before, parents relied heavily on mobiles, but these could be turned off just as easily as the tracking device,” says Dr. Boková.
In his opinion, it is debatable whether in case of attack such a device is really useful.
“If it is a prepared abduction, the perpetrator will practically always check if the child is carrying some kind of electronic device that can reveal its location.”
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices becomes more widespread, it will also look for them, since their sale will undoubtedly be carried out with a lot of publicity."
“In such cases, criminals are always one step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, he adds that such devices can help in the event of an improvised attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Oech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is immediately destroyed, its presence can help.
“You can set the device to regularly send the position after a certain period.”
“If it is damaged, it will at least facilitate the last position of the person in question.”
“The most expensive devices have a tilt meter built-in, so if the person simply slips and stands still, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question,” says Oech.
In his opinion, such a service can be obtained even with mobile phones with navigation, on which only special software must be installed.
The problem with current tracking units is that at the moment they are devices with a similar size to a matchbox or smaller mobile phones.
Therefore, they can get lost.
According to Macro Weil’s Pilin, for that reason tests are currently being conducted with devices that look like a digital clock.
"In addition, they will have the added advantage that a potential attacker may not be able to identify the device."
“Or that I identify him after a while, which can make the police gain time,” he adds.
Even if tracking devices are worn on the wrist or hanging, they will still use the same technology used for vehicle tracking.
This is the position check with a GPS system (which is used in the usual navigation in the car) combined with the function of a mobile phone that communicates the current position.
The army has enough wicks to encircle the whole of the Czech Republic, but they only last two years.
The Czech army bought 445 kilometers of wick to light explosives.
Last year, the Ministry of Defense added 224 kilometers of mecha to its arsenal.
Therefore, they have stock for 225 years.
The problem is that the life of the wick is two years, four at most.
The army bought the explosive wick from the STV Group, a.s. for forty million crowns.
The General’s staff responded to MF DNES by justifying the purchase of such a huge amount of wick by saying that soldiers need 60 kilometers of wick per year for training maneuvers.
According to the calculations of the pyrotechnicians of the army, with whom MF DNES was contacted, however, it is decided that, in such a case, such maneuvers should be carried out with frequent use of explosives every year also all generals, high command officers, and even secretaries and cleaners.
They did not want exempt neither Defense Minister Alexandr Vondr and Army Captain Vlastimil Picek.
Only in this way could it be justified that the army spends sixty kilometers of wick.
Such a length equals 25,000 explosions.
Even if it were, the army would have enough stock for more than ten years.
If on the contrary, as the experts say, for the initial training of each new professional arrives with a maximum of two meters of wick, the army would have with the new purchase (even adding the consumption of the units of engineers or special) sufficient stocks for the 225 indicated above.
The soldiers of the rapid intervention brigade complained personally recently to Minister Vondra because they say they have hardly any ammunition for various weapons, so they limit even the practice of shooting for money.
And let’s not talk about the lack of underwear.
"I also can't understand that they repeatedly buy such quantities of wick from us."
“But it’s their decision and they will certainly know why they act that way.”
“For us, the military is a good customer that we as a company try to satisfy,” admits STV Group’s Chief Commercial Officer Jan Doecki.
Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pejsek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick also saying that it will have stocks of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, STV Group’s Jan D?ck? indicates that the wick only has a useful life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, two years.
“If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four,” says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each munition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm the soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require an additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of wick, he got a discount.
"They cost us 60% less than last year's order of 244 kilometers," said spokesman Pejcek of the Ministry of Defense's procurement center.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of the pyrotechnicians of the police, who eliminate the ammunition of the Second World War or that left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask for only the right amount to exhaust the ammunition before its useful life is over.
They decided it for safety reasons for pyrotechnicians and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable types of wicks can be obtained.
The ministry is already struggling to finish tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the Warsaw Pact era, when the 200,000-strong Czechoslovak army was preparing for a campaign on the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnicians with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years the following problem will occur with the current one: we will have to eliminate hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now being bought "cheap".
