Regulated rents, which benefit residents of around 300,000 flats, could increase next year by as much as 10%.
Young Czechs get drunk on Fernet and rum. The beer is no longer in mode, because it takes effect slowly
Fernet, rum, vodka and even good whiskeys stolen from their parents.
These are the drinks that cause young drinkers with less than fifteen years of age to end up in medical care.
Children who end up lying in the hospital continuously to overcome the hangover are no longer an exception.
This stems from the experience of physicians who encounter such cases in hospital pediatric admissions.
"Drinking beer or wine is no longer fashionable, because they take a long time to get drunk."
"Now the fashion is strong alcoholic beverages," Luduk Pelikan, head of pediatrics at Hocovice Hospital in central Bohemia, told Pravo.
“When they manage to take a bottle from their father’s cupboard, it may be whiskey, but it’s usually Fernet and vodka.”
“Vodka has the advantage of being lightened with juice and not smelling as much,” he explains.
Motol University Hospital spokeswoman Eva Jurinová also confirmed this.
"Normally, it's usually Fernet or rum."
“Those are modern alcoholic beverages, particularly among schoolchildren.”
“In some cases, they use brandy that they picked up at home,” Jurinová adds.
According to Chief Pelikán, it is drinkers between the ages of thirteen and fourteen who usually appear in hospitals.
Prior to this year’s work in Hocovice, he worked for a decade in paediatrics in Motol, where ambulances were taking young people from nearby areas.
"A girl had to come in maybe four times."
"She started at the age of twelve, when she was brought in with 3.5 drops of alcohol in her blood, plus a mixture of ecstasy," the department's doctor says of the case.
"He was at the fair in Holesovice at some dance party."
“The interesting thing is that his mother was not even surprised that her daughter disappeared 48 hours,” the boss is surprised.
It is precisely the lack of interest of parents or even their clear tolerance towards drinking by their children that is considered the main cause of the increase in alcohol consumption among young people.
Experts point out that, in the case of children, one cannot properly speak of dependence.
"Alcoholic means a person who has been chronically dependent on alcohol for several years, with all the phenomena associated with it, which does not occur in children."
“In those who drink alcohol repeatedly, it is more due to a systematically failed social or family environment,” explains Chief Pelikán.
According to spokeswoman Jurinová, forty drunken children were hospitalized in Motol’s pediatric clinic this year until mid-November.
However, statistics only show those who come with severe poisoning and must remain in the hospital.
Young drinkers who go home with their parents or the police after a medical examination do not count.
In addition to the cases in which children simply gather after school and drink aguardiente, for Pelikán there are three seasonal ups and downs that can be mentioned: the witches’ day, New Year’s Eve and the end of the school year.
"In such a circumstance, they drink for bad grades or, on the contrary, celebrate the beginning of the holiday."
“On witch’s day, I’ve seen up to seven drunken children at a time in admissions,” says Pelikán.
Drinkers who spend the night in detoxification under the supervision of doctors, paradoxically, have the advantage that the next day they do not suffer a terrible hangover at home.
Morning headache, caused by dehydration and lack of glucose, is avoided with the injection of a serum with glucose and with the nutrients that the body lacks.
"They get on much better, because after the hectic night, they get up well and nothing hurts."
“They’re just confused about where they are,” says Pelikán, adding that patients often lose their good spirits at least when they see the expenses they’ve generated.
Ambulance transfers and hospitalization in a serious room cost tens of thousands of crowns.
“I have often used cost as a means of educating them, when in the visit I tell them directly to the children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they would have to spend the entire summer in a job for young people so that you would earn enough to pay for yourself that night,” adds Pelikán.
Health insurance, in his opinion perhaps as a retrogressive measure, which usually reimburses people for the costs of treatment, does not do so in the case of children who drink.
