An index finger longer than the ring finger indicates a lower risk of cancer
Men who have the index longer than the null are subject to a lower risk of prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday in a British cancer journal.
It could depend on the level of testosterone, the male hormone.
"Our results indicate that relative finger length may constitute a simple test of prostate cancer risk, particularly for men up to the age of 60," said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
Therefore, the finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, particularly if this characteristic is associated with a genetic risk or other harmful factors, such as family health problems, Eeles says.
During the period 1994-2009, he followed up with a British counterpart more than 1,500 prostate cancer patients and, simultaneously, 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the study participants had the indica finger of the right hand shorter than the ring finger.
They were as likely to have prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were the same length.
For men with a longer index than the ring finger, this risk was reduced by 33%; for men under the age of 60% the reduction reached 87%.
The relationship between the length of the two fingers in question, determined in the prenatal period, reflects different levels of hormones to which the fetus is exposed in the womb.
A lower testosterone level corresponds to a longer index.
Previous studies have indicated that testosterone influences the development of prostate cancer.
The great Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, Professor Václav Pañes, told TK that he is aware of the study, but that he does not think that the relationship between finger length and cancer can be "fully demonstrated".
