The senator’s lawyers announced Wednesday that Justice Department prosecutors have cleared Sen. John Ensign of criminal charges stemming from his affair with a former campaign aide and his efforts to secure lobbying work for the woman’s husband.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat facing Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate for 2012, until the scandal over his affair made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign’s office said it was “surely pleased” by the decision, which came after a full-year investigation.
The senator could still face disciplinary action from the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department had “informed us that Senator Ensign is no longer a target of its investigation and that it has no plan to bring charges against him on this issue.”
The Justice Department declined to comment on the case.
The announcement came as a surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there appeared to be significant evidence to indicate Ensign may have conspired to violate a federal criminal lobbying ban.
Interviews, email and other documents that were first released in October 2009 in the New York Times indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his aides, get lucrative lobbying work to silence Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's affair with her.
Mrs. Hampton once worked as an Ensign campaign treasurer.
Ensign contacted several political backers to find Mr. Hampton a job and advocated on their behalf after they had hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them, according to documents and interviews.
As Hampton had recently been an assistant to Ensign, he was excluded under the lobbying law for his former employer or the Senate for a year.
Ethics experts said the unusual arrangement between Ensign and Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, appeared at odds with the so-called "revolving door lobbying ban," which seeks to restrict former state employees from using their connections to do personal business.
From the evidence that has been made public, “it appeared to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to substantially violate the revolving door statute,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients investigated by the government.
While Justice Department officials declined to explain the reasoning behind the Ensign decision, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared cautious about accepting political prosecutions after several major setbacks for its public integrity section, including last year’s decision to drop prosecution against former Senator Ted Stevens amid charges of procedural misconduct.
Federal prosecutors “are clearly cowards,” said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that brought several complaints against Ensign in the case.
“This basically means that high-ranking government officials can now assume that the laws don’t apply to them,” he added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s lead attorney, said in an interview that he received a phone call from a Justice Department prosecutor on Monday and another call the next day, telling him that the department did not want to press charges against his client.
Ensign’s defense team had been cooperating with prosecutors in attempting to persuade them that the senator, as his office reiterated in a statement Wednesday, “acted in accordance with the law.”
Coggins declined to elaborate on the legal arguments he gave prosecutors.
“I don’t feel comfortable going into details about my discussions with the Department of Justice, I can only say that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to change an investigation into a separate complaint by the ethics group, which alleges that a $96,000 payment from Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The electoral commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove the money was nothing more than a gift.
NV Energy is a major Nevada company that had long supported the senator, who got a lobbying job thanks to Ensign’s help with Hampton.
