Can civility build a bridge to bridge divisions?
After a remarkable campaign for invective and negativity, a bit of civility has broken out in Washington this week.
Is it a harbinger of genuine future bipartisan cooperation or an illusory moment before a quick return to partisan combat in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no progress on the big issues that need to be addressed during the outgoing session.
But from everyone’s point of view, it was at least a courteous discussion of the two sides’ differences, as well as a recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another empty episode to gain partisan points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit commission was equally civilised, despite the political differences that remain between members.
It seems clear that the close interaction over a period of months generated a mutual respect that transcends the ideological gap that still separates members.
That is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Now both sides are in a period of trial, probing each other to identify signs of cooperativism and compromise, as they try to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent evaluations by participants were made with a minimum of demands or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and deep-seated to suggest any rapid climate change that existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, spending, healthcare or welfare, the two sides are at opposite poles.
Anyway, the November election has softened the mood in Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed with regard to the way things are said,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official now at the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“It’s inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse party passions, which are then extinguished.
That's good."
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of the outgoing session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts are due at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of this.
Both sides want to find a way to preserve some or all of the reductions, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, there is likely to be a commitment to expand unemployment benefits, probably because Republicans can’t make believe they are in favor of tax cuts for the wealthy, denying unemployment benefits for unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, there is greater optimism for a possible deal on these issues during the outgoing session, along with the ratification of the new START (Strategic Arms Reduction Treaty) nuclear disarmament pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that successful cooperation on the pressing issues of the outgoing session will not necessarily lead to continued bipartisanship when the new 112th Congress convenes in January.
He claimed, on the contrary, that it is very likely and even inevitable that a period of disagreement will begin.
“After the things that need to be done are done, in the short term psychology will revert the situation to one of confrontation,” he said.
Wehner also expressed skepticism (which is widely shared) about the fact that civility can lead to real cooperation.
“I see most of what will happen between now and 2012 as a rehearsal for the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons have a lot to do with the constitution of the new Republican majority in the House and the Tea Party voters, who contributed decisively to its creation.
As much as Republican leaders are aware of the dangers of overstating their position, they know they must try to keep their promises to cut state spending and repeal the new health care law.
Those party lines are already clearly seen in the initial reactions to the deficit commission recommendations, which include reforming the tax code and raising some taxes and raising the retirement age, and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have taken on one of the most difficult jobs in Washington and, by their own assessment, have forcibly introduced the deficit issue onto the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to publish their plan as an official recommendation, and have been struggling to get close to that figure.
The greatest resistance is among the elected officials on the panel, suggesting that on fiscal issues there is, at least today, little basis or desire for compromise.
Galston predicts two phases in the battles between White House and congressional Republicans.
The first will happen next year in the form of partisan clashes, when Republicans challenge Obama on budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of increased bipartisan cooperation.
What would cause the change?
Public opinion.
There is considerable evidence that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties working together.
If confrontation leads to a stalemate, as happened in 1995, then both parties will watch the reaction of the people closely.
Whoever they think is losing is likely to change course and seek compromise.
However, this may be an optimistic view.
The partisanship and polarization are now greater than they were in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a larger ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans at the time.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as the mere prelude to a more momentous election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility shown this week can be welcomed by many Americans.
But this will require much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
