Shoemaker and the German Red Line
Berlin has chosen to stay in the euro but has set the conditions for the whole Union.
Tensions in the markets have provoked a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodríguez Zapatero has advanced new adjustment measures, from tax reductions to SMEs, regulation of private placement agencies or elimination of the 426 euros of aid to the unemployed without provision, to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of State Lotteries.
On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe González, has joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel for her responsibility in unleashing the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
Go ahead that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another twist in the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future must be, which clashes with that of maintaining the old traditions of many of its partners.
Faced with European resistance, in Germany there is speculation about the three possible ways out of the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, made up of itself, Austria and the Netherlands, among other countries, while the south would leave the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the framework, although it now seems science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, close to 50% of the population.
The third, a redesign of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigour, fines to the transgressor countries, possible suspensions of payments of some of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there are no excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were stimulating deficits, the German government scrapped a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany believed should be done (plans of fiscal rigour and stability in public finances), and what its European partners, including France, were practicing.
The second in the forehead was given by the Central European country when Merkel painfully extended the decision of rescue of Greece.
Already then it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and public opinion and published it were very much against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, again Merkel emerges with a clear position, demanding the reform of the treaties of the Union, to make possible the rescue of a country and, at the same time, to force private lenders to bear part of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it has precipitated the Irish crisis and everything else.
But his proposal, although somewhat sweetened, has been approved and, in the coming months, we should attend the process of reform of the Union that enables those measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
And it is telling all of us that, although we must now take measures with which we may not agree very much, from that date the old functioning of the euro will be over.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary area, in which the offending countries will be severely sanctioned, they can be forced to declare in suspension of payments and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is signaling to us that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
Another alternative based on debt and construction, with huge holes in the balance of payments, such as the one that has presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, they will simply not tolerate it.
The envy is clear.
And we would do wrong not to understand it.
It’s not just about bringing the government deficit back to 3% in 2013.
What we are required to do is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater tranquillity.
And let’s take advantage of the window of opportunity they have given us, until spring 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday’s meeting with big companies and yesterday’s announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite the criticism of Merkel, the thesis that it is necessary to put order at home has made its way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and it doesn’t look like they’re going to move it.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, to leave a monetary zone too crowded with unserious countries, it cannot be excluded.
Then, Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and Law Fraud
Shots like Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the will to escape a penalty.
The expulsion allegedly concocted by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the match played on November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has caused rivers of ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, with only a few minutes left to finish the game (which their team clearly had already won), the two players deliberately lost time when it came to taking the fouls to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
That way, and since Real Madrid will end up as leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next game of the league, against Auxerre, and they will be able to pass clean of cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA disciplinary committee has sanctioned the team's coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and with different economic amounts to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate that arose in the case reported is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and that on past occasions has fined its players for analogous acts) and the dramatization orchestrated, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds one more episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative coach.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behavior not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, if these actions are committed fraud of law; because, in fact, they are actions respectful of the sports regulations, but they seem to avoid their meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to sportsmanship.
One of the assets that includes sportsmanship is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not endangered, that is, there was no violent game.
Another of these assets that is alluded to with fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that they did not accommodate what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud of law, because their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely their action tried to be the most evident in order to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders gain in the intentional faults examined.
Here it seems necessary to verify that the opponent is not placed at a disadvantage or profit in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team itself with fewer players.
And it is not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club will not be able to count on those players.
The advantage, obviously, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team can be eliminated at the first exchange, and also with this action the players fulfill a sanction match and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension for accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the sporting spirit, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without getting around the punishment or running away from it.
Although the boundary between wit and law fraud is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of wit.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them was carried out.
The damage caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not so much ethical as aesthetic.
