“The interesting thing is that I’ve been making progress in every competition.”
"At this rate, I'll be the first this time or next year!"
The "san shou" or "sanda" is a discipline originally from China in which it is allowed to hit with the fists and feet, as well as throw opponents to the ground.
Clashes are originally held on a platform and, less frequently, in a ring.
The most famous pugilist in this type of combat is the Vietnamese-born American Cung Le, widely recognized in the martial arts world.
Although Nacer Zemmal only has to maintain a competition in his career, he will undoubtedly attend the great "King of Sanda" tournament, the Super Bowl of kung-fu.
"This competition is the most notorious and prestigious in China," explains the friendly boy.
“It’s like the equivalent of Lumpinee Stadium (Thailand’s biggest stadium).”
“It’s been an amazing experience.”
Zemmal has won his first match, in the semi-finals of his category (80 kg), but lost in the final.
“The one who beat me is a real professional,” he says.
"There are four competitors per category (80 kg, 85 kg, 90 kg and 90 kg)."
"Semifinal winners face off in their category final".
"Next, the champions of each category face off to crown a single champion, the king of kung-fu."
$450 million in non-tender contracts
Hydro-Québec has awarded $450 million in direct contracts to engineering companies for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than a hundred contracts is a consortium formed by the companies BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor, which has obtained without a prior tender the most important contract, that of project management, for a sum of 295 million.
The consortium, called Énergie gérance, was created in 2004 following Hydro-Québec’s decision to entrust the private sector with its responsibility for managing this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the Énergie gérance consortium won the lucrative contract without a public tender.
For the Quebec Party, the use of consortiums of companies poses a serious ethical problem that threatens to eliminate competition and cause a rise in prices.
“This is a new method of collusion and eliminating competition.”
"That is, the people, instead of doing it in secret, now do it openly," Quebec Party MP Sylvain Simard told a news conference yesterday.
Earlier in the morning, Mr Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because, he claims, he does not understand how it can benefit the public interest in this way.
Natural Resources Minister Nathalie Normandeau responded in the afternoon, firmly denying that collusion with this contract has occurred.
“I’m starting to get tired,” he protested, arguing that the PQ had acted “dishonestly” and “with lack of rigor.”
He said the “minimum” would be for the PQ to apologize.
The consortia formula is a common practice throughout the world.
Typically, this is a partnership with a time limit that allows two or more companies to pool their knowledge to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project presents a high level of complexity, taking into account the magnitude of the works.
The works have already begun and will last until 2012.
In all cases, the contract was awarded without competition; it was a negotiation.
In addition, the consortia formula is no longer the exception to the standard in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir published last week, the formula of the consortia in the field of technical advice is being subjected to an investigation in the Government.
A quick look at Quebec’s trade register allows you to identify more than 200 consortia, some of which seem permanent.
In this way, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, such as CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin, Roche et Tecsult, and others.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, leads to a single legal person, that is, Dessau.
Regarding the Énergie gérance consortium, Minister Normandeau stressed that "the James Bay territory responds to a particular labor dynamics and Hydro-Québec responds specifically to it since the 1970s."
The head of the Eastmain project, Réal Laporte, of the Société d'énergie de la Baie James (SEBJ), has given an explanation that has highlighted the fact that the project management contract has been granted directly.
“If you respond to a tender and there are few participants, your prices are going to be higher.”
"You have two options: you can get in touch with the players in the sector and tell them: we are going to negotiate a satisfactory agreement and with a good price."
"However, the idea is that what matters is not the price, but the competition of people," Mr Laporte said.
The contract awarded to the Énergie gérance consortium is part of a long list of contracts worth more than $50,000 obtained by the Québec Party.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
Following verification, Le Devoir has identified 109 technical advisory contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to companies or their subsidiaries, in particular geotechnical laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin has won 22 contracts, Génivar has won 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, without taking into account its participation in Énergie gérance.
All contracts were negotiated.
In total, they amount to $449,783,344, including Énergie gérance ' s contract of $295,131,564.
Sylvain Simard has implied that the four companies that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "well-known to the Liberal Party of Quebec".
Minister Normandeau has dropped that the PQ is also linked to these companies, which "finance" it, before specifying that it is more about their leaders.
Barometer of responsible consumption. The "green" label does not inspire confidence
Greener, but deeply skeptical.
The Quebec consumer has little faith in sustainable development actors, as well as fair trade brands and green certificates to guide their choices.
According to the Barometer of responsible consumption, whose first results were published yesterday, the situation is even worse. The consumer is immersed in a media universe where messages that defend more responsible consumption swarm, but regrets the lack of reliable information and considers that this even slows down their commitment.
Even if consumption of so-called “socially responsible” products has increased in 2010, Quebecers seem to give very little credit to those trying to sell them.
Two-thirds of them say, in fact, that they do not trust the environmental commitment of companies or the environmental advertising of them, reveals the measurement tool prepared by the Observatory of responsible consumption of the University of Sherbrooke.
Another conclusion: half of consumers question the reliability of official certificates that carry so-called fair products, as well as the credibility of products and brands that bear labels indicating that they are “equivalent,” the Barometer notes.
Similarly, only 14.6 per cent of Quebecers take politicians’ speeches on this issue seriously.
In any case, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this consumer sector, currently supported by about a third of Quebec consumers.
In fact, the gaps and doubtful nature of the information mean that 46% of consumers discard this option.
This is the second obstacle identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, a third of Quebecers say they also distrust the supposed returns of the ecological products or services that they are trying to sell.
Moreover, almost half of consumers changed their habits in 2010 and, especially, changed the brand of one or several products to respect their convictions.
61% have given priority to shopping in their neighborhood stores and have preferred to buy food products grown in their region, says the Barometer.
Greener and more responsible (the index of responsible consumption has reached 64 points out of a maximum of one hundred this year), the Homo consumerus of Quebec loves to occupy the position of the king of recycling that tries to reduce its impact on the environment by worrying about the protection of the fauna.
However, according to the Barometer, that social awareness seems to be from outside: in 2010, only 28% of Quebecers indicated that they have used public transport or have shared a car to defend their environmental principles.
In addition, 39.1% of participants in this comprehensive behavioural survey, which has just completed its first edition, support cycling and walking.
