However, Christian Yaccarini has not contacted Le Devoir again and we do not know what he and his group think of the downward proposals they have received.
The veil of Canada is lifted.
The new U.S. diplomatic cables released by WikiLeaks reveal what the U.S. regards as the Canadians’ complex with respect to the Americans, but at the same time reflect the latter’s sense of superiority towards Canada.
U.S. diplomats are surprised that Canadian voters don’t think about Canada-U.S. relations when they go to vote and believe that President Obama’s visit has helped the Conservative government get its budget passed in 2009!
The four new communications between the U.S. Embassy in Ottawa and Washington that were made public yesterday offer more juicy details than really substantial content.
A cable dated September 22, 2008, that is, during the full federal election campaign, recounts the extent to which the United States does not enter into the issues debated by political leaders.
This caused great surprise to the American ambassador sent to Ottawa, David Wilkins.
Mr. Wilkins offers some explanations on this situation.
“Perhaps political leaders are conditioned by an inferiority complex virtually inherent in dealing with everyday domestic issues, rather than leaving such an election to the United States (as during the 1988 free trade campaign),” he writes.
Consequently, he concludes, the United States is “the proverbial elephant of this choice: omnipresent, but potentially too dangerous to talk about.”
The ambassador has even more trouble understanding this “deafening silence” because the two countries maintain intense political and economic relations.
“Logically, he believes, the ability of a candidate, a party, and even more, a party leader to manage these essential relationships should be a key factor voters should think about when voting.”
This feeling of importance can also be seen in the cable sent on January 22, 2009 by Terry Breese, charge d’affaires in Ottawa, to prepare President Barack Obama for his first visit to Ottawa.
“His trip will help ensure the survival of the government during the vote of confidence in early February on the federal budget, whereby Canada will run deficits for the first time in the last decade due to a recovery plan of between $30 billion and $40 billion,” Breese writes.
Nowhere is there any mention that the government had to extend Parliament before Christmas to prevent the coalition from replacing it or that opposition parties conditioned its survival on the quality of the proposed recovery plan.
Another communication from January 2008 signed by Ambassador Wilkins alerts Washington to the increasingly negative image conveyed by the drama series broadcast on the CBC in the United States.
The ambassador is concerned about the issuance of Border, Little Mosque on the Prairie, Intelligence and H2O, in which little subtle references are made to Maher Arar, the “No-Fly-List” or even kidnappings for the CIA to perform energetic interrogations.
Another cable says that during their first bilateral meeting, Hillary Clinton asked her French counterpart Bernard Kouchner if Europe would be willing to take in some Guantánamo prisoners.
Mr. Kouchner replied that he did, but that it depended "on each case."
At the end of the meeting, they wrote, “You have delivered a document to the Secretary of State regarding Omar Khadr, a 15-year-old Muslim of Canadian origin.”
"The Secretary agreed to review the file."
Finally, we can mention that tempers have warmed in relation to the WikiLeaks site.
Tom Flanagan, Stephen Harper’s longtime close adviser, told CBC radio that the man responsible for this massive leak should be “killed.”
In the United States they echo Mike Huckabee.
A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
Yesterday, the UN proposed in Cancun a plan to renew domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in one hundred countries to reduce greenhouse gases (GHGs) by an amount that corresponds to almost a third of the additional decrease that must be carried out to stabilize the planet’s climate before 2020.
This ambitious plan is part of the set of concrete large projects that the UN expects to be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if incandescent bulbs, which still monopolize between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluo-compact bulbs or, even better, by bulbs of electroluminescent diodes (DELs or “LEDs”), much of the 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GHG emitted on the planet to illuminate humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary car park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that were to lower global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, 5 Gt of this amount should still be decreased to stabilize, before 2020, the increase in temperatures by two degrees Celsius to prevent it from getting out of control.
In incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, that is, 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluocompact bulbs, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, energy consumption is still reduced twice more.
Fluocompact bulbs last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, like those launched by the manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which allows us to get an idea of the savings that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in a hundred countries.
These new bulbs can also work with rheostats and emit very little heat.
Above, they do not contain any mercury.
Specialists have expressed reservations about fluo-compact bulbs, as they contain mercury and must be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries unless manufacturers issue instructions.
However, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not fluocompact light bulbs, but coal-fired power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that is wasted by incandescent light bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the advantages that this international program would offer to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save one billion dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, that is, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
Ivory Coast looks forward to the announcement of the election results
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has called for the “immediate” publication of the results of the presidential elections in Ivory Coast, given that the deadlines have expired.
“The Secretary-General stresses the need for the independent electoral commission to complete its work and announce the provisional results immediately,” a spokesman for the UN chief said.
“Call on all parties in Ivory Coast and the institutions to demonstrate their sense of responsibility and refrain from any initiative until provisional results are announced.”
Despite pressure from some foreign governments, the electoral commission has allowed Wednesday's midnight deadline to pass without the results being released, three days since Sunday's vote.
About forty minutes before the end of the deadline, the president of the CIS had told television that the commission “was still working” to announce the results.
Calls for the CIS to finally proclaim the name of the winner of the second round between outgoing Laurent Gbagbo and his opponent Alassane Ouattara have multiplied in the world on Wednesday.
However, Gbagbo’s side is counting on the Constitutional Council to annul the “fraudulent” votes in the north, at the hands of the old rebellion of the New Forces (FN) since the failed coup d’état of September 2002.
Pascal Affi N’Guessan, campaign manager for the president of Ivory Coast, said the FN’s voter intimidation maneuvers in the north of the country had deterred supporters of the outgoing president from going to vote.
The entire election could be annulled if the Constitutional Council accepts Gbagbo’s complaints.
Gbagbo’s opponents consider the country’s highest court to be non-neutral, as it is led by Paul Yao N’Dré, a close political ally of Gbagbo.
Alassane Ouattara, a man from the north who denies any relationship with the former rebels, has judged the delay in publishing the results "unacceptable" and has asked Gbagbo to respect them, but has not gone so far as to claim victory.
His allies claim that Gbagbo blocks the publication of the results because he knows he has lost and that filing a complaint with the Constitutional Council after having prevented the electoral commission from disseminating the results would be illegal.
The second round of the presidential elections, on Sunday, should have put an end to the process of reunification and reconciliation of a country divided in two for years.
The United Nations on Wednesday warned Ivory Coast’s political class that they could be held responsible for possible acts of violence.
Laurent Gbagbo had finished in the first round, on 31 October, with 38% of the vote compared to 32% for Alassane Ouattara, who publicly received the support of former president Henri Konan Bédié (25% in the first round).
Unemployment rate remains stable in France in the third quarter
According to the International Labour Organization (ILO), the unemployment rate in France has remained stable at 9.3% in the mainland (9.7% taking into account the overseas departments), as indicated by the data corrected with the provisional seasonal variations (CVE) published on Thursday by Insee.
The number of unemployed remains at 2,631,000 in mainland France.
The data for the second quarter have been confirmed, 9.3% of the labor force in the continental territory and 9.7% with the DOM.
In one year, the unemployment rate has increased by 0.1 points.
Overall, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter, but they want to work, whether or not they are available in the two weeks to work and whether or not they are looking for work.
The situation of young people in the labour market has continued to worsen, with a further increase in the unemployment rate to 24.2% in mainland France (+0.9 points in three months, +0.5 points in one year), 25% including DOMs.
During the third quarter, 637,000 young people between the ages of 15 and 24 were unemployed within the meaning of the ILO.
For its part, there has been a slight increase in unemployment among the elderly, up to 6.4% in continental France (+0.2 points in three months and one year), that is, 482,000 people over 50 years old, a figure that amounts to 6.6% with the DOMs.
Unemployment has only been stable among people aged between 25 and 49 years, with 8.3% in continental France (-0.1 points in three months, +0.1 points in one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
The Insee has not published the monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after a controversy over its methods of calculation.
Eurostat, the European Union’s statistics agency, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a 9.8% rate for France (DOM included) in October, up from 9.9% in September.
