Clotilde Reiss: Elisha has exaggerated Syria’s mediation
For more than ten months, between July 2009 and May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young French researcher detained in Iran for “espionage,” has been on the lookout for the public in France, alerting diplomacy and accentuating the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful eye of U.S. diplomats.
U.S. documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal certain unknown aspects of this crisis.
They describe how the Elisha has explained his strategy to the Americans to the point of giving them advice to manage their own “hostage” crises in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials tried to convince Washington that the release of the young Frenchwoman did not come about in exchange for the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian arrested in France and wanted by US justice for trafficking materials for the Iranian nuclear program.
Finally, they reveal the stark reality of how the French presidency attempted to manipulate the media to give the idea that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad had played an essential role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
Actually, he didn't do anything.
A diplomatic telegram written on 12 August 2009 in Paris bears the title "Iran: French comments on how to manage hostage-taking cases".
The Elysee’s advisor for strategic affairs, Francois Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d’Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, speak with the US diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
Explain the French method.
They advise Americans to do the following to repatriate their own citizens forcibly held in Iran.
“Make noise,” they say, “continually release” in the media the words “fundamental human rights,” “innocence,” “immediate release.”
All to shame the Iranian regime, careful of its image.
“When Iranians ask you to stop, do it even more often.”
Because, once the attempts to negotiate through discreet channels have been exhausted, "silence will not solve anything", the Iranians are "experts in delaying maneuvers".
Mr Richier adds that the detention of foreigners is “a common Iranian tactic: the taking of hostages for political blackmail”.
He announces that the release from prison of Clotilde Reiss (which will occur on August 16, the day she will take refuge in the French embassy) “will require the payment to the Iranians of a large amount of money” (230,000 euros of reward).
In addition, he points out that the Elisha anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that “is going to increase.”
The Iranians could “in the near future detain another of the about 1,800 French citizens living in Iran,” he says.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss is released from prison after 12 days, but she is blocked in Iran.
The following information was disseminated: the Iranian Majid Kakavand, whose extradition the United States requested for illicit trafficking of sensitive electronic material into Iran, had been released in Paris by a judge ' s decision.
The U.S. Embassy, like many observers, doubts this strange coincidence.
For Washington, which is closing Iran’s clandestine nuclear procurement networks, the release of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Has France accepted an exchange?
Releasing the Iranian in exchange for the French?
During a new conversation with Kathleen Allegrone, on September 4, Francois Richier guarantees that this was not the case.
Elisha, he says, has not only “been greatly surprised by the judge’s decision,” but has attempted to oppose it.
“There have been intense negotiations between the French presidency and the Minister of Justice” (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but “the French government cannot overturn the judicial decision,” he says.
Mr Richier also wants to prove that Majid Kakavand is still under the "narrow" surveillance of the French intelligence services.
Elisha’s adviser dials a phone number, hangs up and then informs the U.S. diplomat that the Iranian “is currently in Paris buildings run by the Iranian embassy.”
During the arrest of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elysee spares no effort, using statements and "leaks" organized in the media to make believe that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad plays an "important" and "influential" role of "mediator".
The Americans observe this activity with a certain irony and see that the manipulation bears fruit, since several press articles transmit the official French version.
A telegram dated 25 August 2009 mentions "the media blitz of French officials".
What is the reason for this “gratitude” towards Mr. Assad, the embassy in Paris wonders.
“Despite their praiseworthy statements, French officials privately acknowledge that they have only a vague idea of what the Syrians have really done.”
Next, the document deals with the reasons that have led Elisha to give rise to this fiction.
The communication effort “is aimed at validating Sarkozy’s policy of opening up to Syria,” he said.
A policy initiated in 2008, which "in the opinion of numerous critical voices in France and abroad, had just been branded as premature and undeserved."
By “exaggerating the Syrian role,” Paris tries to “show Syria the praise it can reap if it plays a constructive role in the region.”
The goal is also to “sow the seed of discord between Syria and Iran.”
The U.S. Embassy knows this from a good source.
On August 11, Francois Richier confides in him: “Of course, we don’t know if the Syrians have done anything or not.”
“But anyway, we thanked him.”
“At the very least, this should lead to confusion among Iranians.”
