Hackers Avengers and Diligent Spies
The WikiLeaks affair has a double value.
On the one hand, it reveals an apparent scandal, a scandal that only seems scandalous in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between States, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it announces profound changes on an international scale and foresees a future dominated by regression.
But let's go step by step.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is confirmation of the fact that every file created by a secret service (regardless of the nation to which it belongs) is made up exclusively of press clippings.
The “extraordinary” American revelations about Berlusconi’s sexual mores only reflect what has been written for months in any newspaper (except those belonging to Berlusconi) and Gaddafi’s sinisterly ridiculed profile has long given cabaret artists ideas to create their sketches.
The rule that secret files should only be made up of news in the public domain is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not just in this century.
If you visit a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each work repeats (about the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Chéteau, the Templars or the Rosicrucians) exactly what had been written in the previous works.
This is not only because the authors of occult texts do not want to do unpublished research (or do not know where to look for news about the non-existent), but because those who dedicate themselves to the occult not only trust what they already know, what reconfirms what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
The same applies to secret files.
The informer is lazy, just as he is lazy (or has little desire) the head of the secret services (if he could not be, I do know, editor of the Libération), who only considers true what he can recognize.
The top-secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as that published by Newsweek the week before.
So why have the revelations in these files caused such a stir?
On the one hand, they only say what every cultivated person already knows, that is, that embassies, at least since World War II and since Heads of States can call each other or take the plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of some limited representation exercises, have been transformed into spy centers.
Any viewer who watches investigative films knows this perfectly well, we just pretend we don’t know it out of hypocrisy.
In any case, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy and gives a bad image of American diplomacy.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can consult the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world greatly affects the prestige of the State Department.
Therefore, the scandal affects both the victims and the "executors".
But let’s get into the true nature of what has happened.
In former times, in Orwell’s time, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
Orwell’s prophecy has come true since, being able to control every movement thanks to the telephone, every transaction made, hotel visited, highway taken, the citizen thus became a complete victim of the eye of power.
But when it is shown, as it is now, that not even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the relationship of control ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen (at least the hacker, chosen as the citizen’s avenger) can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power endure that can no longer even keep its own secrets?
It is true, as Georg Simmel said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that all knowledge about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is in fact an empty secret, without secret, since it comes from the public sphere; but to reveal, as WikiLeaks has done, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means to take away all power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done a lot to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound caused to such a powerful power?
It is clear that, in the future, States will no longer be able to post any classified information online, since it would be like posting it on a poster in the street.
But it’s also clear that with today’s technologies, you can’t expect to have confidential conversations over the phone.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a Head of State has flown in and contacted one of the counterparts.
How will they be able to maintain private and confidential relationships in the future?
I know perfectly well that, for the moment, my foresight is a matter of science fiction and, therefore, novelistic, but I imagine government agents who travel discreetly in errands with uncontrollable itineraries, carrying messages that have been learned by heart or, at most, hiding some data written on the heels of their shoes.
That information is then preserved, in a single copy, in locked drawers: in the end, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
In the past, I have written that technology currently advances like a crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has re-created a wired (telephone) telegraph.
Videotapes (analog) had allowed film researchers to study a film step by step, moving forward and backward, uncovering all the secrets of montage, while now CDs (digital) only allow to move forward or backward from chapter to chapter, that is, to enormous proportions.
With high-speed trains, we can get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, with the travel it entails, we need three and a half hours.
Therefore, it is nothing out of the ordinary for politics and communication techniques to take us back to horse-drawn carriages.
One last comment.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was secretly being plotted in embassies.
At present, it is the embassies that request confidential information from the press.
Climate: France’s botches in its funding pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unlocked funding pledges (called fast start or early) made by developed countries have been respected.
And the French botches have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to provide $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (i.e. 420 million a year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has put its best cards on the table to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start financing is true: a report detailing the measures of its member states, a press conference, a large complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparency operation was appreciable and appreciated for what it really was: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and with the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of EUR 7.2 billion in 2012.
But, if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Accord, the money must be “new and additional” to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without harming official development assistance.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has taken as a reference the year 2009: international financing is maintained and 150 million are added in three years as fast start financing.
Other countries have chosen similar benchmarks in terms of the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers the financing of "all new projects" for 2010 to be "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to expenditures in previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries may remain stable (or even decline), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds...
Another crucial element, the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no standard and everyone chooses the method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider each euro borrowed to be equivalent to a donated euro.
Evidently, such a thing is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans may be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions that are based on more effective technologies), it is fallacious to present a euro that is going to be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is donated ... At most, only the cost of the loan should be computed for its commitments for the country that grants the loan (that is, the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France does not find such reasoning useful: it “respects” its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); consult the EU document to see it for yourself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so frequently.
Germany uses it by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union contributes one euro to meet its commitment, France only contributes ten cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
A good trick!
In short, in its fast start financing, France performs a double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to actions over time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
Spending only 36.1 million euros, he manages to give the impression that he spends 420 million "new and additional", as he had promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who has dealt with arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to donate when they can simply lend?) and in negotiations, since developing countries are not fools...
The chapter on early financing is a relatively short-term minutiae of the climate negotiations as a whole.
But it could be an extra grain of sand in the immense machinery that is the UNFCCC.
Let's hope it doesn't.
Whatever it is, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its calculation method for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, especially, France could move the debates on the stakes in relation to long-term financing forward (another essential chapter that is currently being debated): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method for computing loans.
France could change its stance to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore have the hope of the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additional character” and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move the negotiations forward.
Warning about pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old boy ingests 81 different chemicals on one day, according to a study published Wednesday by the association Générations Futures (the ancient movement for rights and respect for future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "do not have significant statistical value taking into account the limited number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem treated", acquired in supermarkets in Oise and Paris between July and September the foods that a child of about ten years old usually consumes in four meals and a snack a day.
These model meals, which comply with official recommendations (five parts fresh fruits and vegetables, three parts dairy products and 1.5 liters of water a day), as well as treats, were examined in laboratories for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other contaminants.
The balance of the dish is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, of which 42 classified as possible or probable carcinogens and five substances classified as safe carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors (EPs), according to studies by various institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
“Although, in virtually all cases, the legal limits for individual chemicals are not exceeded, our study clearly shows that consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic contaminants and/or PE is of concern,” the association said.
For breakfast, butter and tea with milk alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogenic residues and three considered as safe carcinogens, as well as about twenty residues that can harm the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for school, contains traces of six chemicals, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same applies to Kenyan green beans, included in food, where the study has detected traces of a potent insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, Russian steak, canned tuna, and even loaf of bread or gum were seasoned with pesticides and other chemicals.
In the tap water, analyses found the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
At dinner, the salmon slice was the most “nutritive” with 34 chemical residues detected and even the analysis of the plastic dish used to heat the food in the microwave was not completely clean.
The ultimate risk these “contaminant cocktails” generate for the consumer “is likely to be underestimated,” the study says.
The Europe Ecology-Les Verts Alliance (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "against the gravity of the situation" to apply a moratorium on the use of pesticides to curb "the increase in diseases associated with civilization".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) indicated the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in the fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, of which 76 in cereals.
